            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>The sex metaphor even has room for subversive elements. Consider this comment appended to another text by &ldquo;nzrayza&rdquo;: &ldquo;I like how it&rsquo;s now &lsquo;canonical&rsquo; (!) that Big John is mesmerised by Little John&rsquo;s &lsquo;warmth&rsquo; and his neck. I like how you take that canon and build on it by adding the smell (Edwards <em>looks</em> like he&rsquo;d smell good!). I like how Edwards is the one who&rsquo;s really in control, from remembering the press to taking command in the bedroom.&rdquo; Just as Foucault&rsquo;s model would predict, K/E slash characterizes the running-mates&rsquo; relationship as much more multifaceted than a straightforward top-to-bottom one.</p>
<p>Let&rsquo;s look at one last text, this one a rare instance of Kerry/Gephardt slash, composed by &ldquo;marcusaurelius1&rdquo;:</p>
<p>&ldquo;Dick, there&rsquo;s no easy way to tell you this... There&rsquo;s another man.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The former House Minority Leader&rsquo;s muscles tensed in a brief spasm of agony, but Kerry&rsquo;s hand was suffered to remain where it was. &ldquo;Let me guess,&rdquo; Dick said. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s some pretty young thing you met in the Senate.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s not like that! Listen to me, Dick, no one can ever replace you or your sterling ties to organized labor or your comprehensive national healthcare plan or, sweet Jesus, those eyebrows&mdash;not now, not ever. It&rsquo;s just that the American people demand&mdash;&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Shut up! Kiss me, John Forbes Kerry.&rdquo;</p>
<p>We see, of course, the same tendencies at work. The writer reconceptualizes Gephardt&rsquo;s rejection to be running-mate as romantic rejection and employs a trope that recasts the Congressman&rsquo;s constituencies (&ldquo;organized labor&rdquo;) as physically attractive attributes on par with &ldquo;those eyebrows.&rdquo; At the same time, Gephardt emerges not as abject victim but rather as sexo-political aggressor.</p>
<ol>
<li>Further reading</li>
</ol>

